{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531807"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:19:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:19:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14630"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14630"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.29,0.16,0.17,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7323"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102439"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7323"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14630"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84913"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1708"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"3806"},{"type":"tags","id":"4025"},{"type":"tags","id":"4050"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17883"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35692"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102439"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman is admitted to the medical ward with worsening headache. She has known metastatic breast cancer with multiple brain metastases diagnosed three months ago. She declined whole brain radiotherapy and is receiving best supportive care. She does not take any regular medications except for as-needed paracetamol. She lives in a nursing home.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt 3 AM, nursing staff find her slumped in bed with a markedly reduced conscious level. She is restless with intermittent groaning and appears distressed. She cannot be roused to voice but withdraws from painful stimuli. Her right arm and leg are flaccid with no movement. Her pulse rate is 42/min, blood pressure 184/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 26/min with apnoeic periods, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous dexamethasone","Intravenous mannitol","Urgent neurosurgical referral","Subcutaneous midazolam","Intravenous vitamin K"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is likely experiencing a catastrophic intracranial haemorrhage in the setting of known brain metastases. She demonstrates evidence of Cushing\u0027s triad: bradycardia, hypertension with wide pulse pressure, and irregular breathing likely representing Cheynes-Stokes breathing. This is a late sign of brainstem dysfunction, indicative of increased intracranial pressure. Given her advanced cancer and the clinical severity of the presumed bleed, this represents a terminal event. The focus should be on providing comfort and dignity in her final hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous midazolam\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management as it provides rapid sedation and comfort in this distressing situation. The goal is to ensure the patient is not aware of or distressed by the symptoms of massive haemorrhage. Midazolam can be given as a stat dose followed by a continuous infusion if required. If the course of events is prolonged or there is pain or distress, there is evidence for addition of a strong opioid, in this case subcutaneous morphine may be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent neurosurgical referral\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate given the terminal nature of her underlying condition and the catastrophic nature of the presumed bleed, with Cushing\u0027s triad portending poor prognosis from the outset. Surgical intervention would not alter the outcome and may prolong suffering.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous mannitol\u003C/strong\u003E is used to reduce intracranial pressure in situations where there is potential for meaningful recovery. In this terminal situation, it would not change the outcome and may prolong the dying process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous dexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E would not meaningfully impact the outcome of an acute intracerebral haemorrhage. While steroids can help reduce vasogenic oedema around metastases, they are not indicated in this terminal situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous vitamin K\u003C/strong\u003E would not meaningfully alter the outcome of an established massive intracranial haemorrhage, particularly in this terminal context. There is no mention of anticoagulation in her medication list.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Terminal events in advanced cancer require a focus on comfort and rapid symptom control rather than futile interventions.","Midazolam is the preferred agent for rapid sedation in catastrophic intracranial events at end of life.","Escalation to neurosurgical or aggressive medical management is not appropriate in the context of established catastrophic brain injury and advanced malignancy."],"references":["Harris DG, Noble SI. Management of terminal hemorrhage in patients with advanced cancer: a systematic literature review. J Pain Symptom Manage. 2009;38(6):913-927. doi:10.1016/j.jpainsymman.2009.04.027. Available online at ; https://www.jpsmjournal.com/article/S0885-3924(09)00736-2/fulltext","Parry-Jones AR, Moullaali TJ, Ziai WC. Treatment of intracerebral hemorrhage: From specific interventions to bundles of care. International Journal of Stroke. 2020 Dec;15(9):945-53. Available online at ; https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.1177/1747493020964663"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84913"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14630"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84913"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-12T18:47:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T18:49:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7323"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102439"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms